	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Chifari</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Initiate<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jun 2003<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Hi,<br />
<br />
In the spirit of Chutoi's post, I am going to propose a whole bunch of upgrades/possible fixes to the problems he mentioned.  I am a 65 Time-enabled shaman, so my ideas are geared toward endgame play, for the most part.  I've tried to think of things that would be of general benefit to all shammies, however.  A lot of these aren't my ideas, either, but the effort of the entire shaman community that posts on this board, so kudos to ya... and here we go!...<br />
<br />
<h2>Slow</h2><br />
<br />
The core ability of the shaman class.  99.99% of shamans agree that we should be able to slow better than any other class.  That means our slow should dominate.  There should not be situations where you say "A BST would slow this mob better."  BST, as a hybrid, should be able to fulfill the slowing role, but its slow should not 'step on' the shaman one at all.  Currently it does, and this is a problem.<br />
<br />
We need to either slow more (80%, which I don't think will happen), or get a slow that is at least as good as the BST (1.5 sec cast, 65%, easy to land).  I would propose a 1.5 second cast, 300 mana, 70% slow with a 5 second recast (same as BST) that lasts a bit longer than theirs (4 mins).  <br />
<br />
There are also more creative ideas, such as tacking slow onto something that is a disadvantage in some situations, i.e. slow+nuke or slow+DoT in a single spell (so you couldn't use it on adds).  A cold based slow+nuke could be particularly interesting and good for fast-paced situations.<br />
<br />
Might look something like:<br />
<br />
<b>Frigid Cocoon</b><br />
1.  Decrease HP by 1100 when cast<br />
2.  Decrease attack speed by 50%<br />
Mana:  450, Casting Time:  5.0, Duration:  1.0 mins, Recast Time:  2<br />
<br />
A 50% slow would be about 125mana (imo) and Velium Strike 300, so 450 is a reasonable cost for something that isn't as effective as Turgur's slow-wise and nukes for more than VS.  The main thing you gain is *time*, which is one of shamans' principal problems atm.  Our spells are so slow that we don't have time to cast the fun stuff.  This spell gives us a bigger nuke but at a price (more mana, slow tacked on), but also would give us a new slow resist (cold).<br />
<br />
A cold-based slow DoT might look something like:<br />
<br />
<b>Frigid Withering</b><br />
1.  Decrease attack speed by 50%<br />
2.  Decrease HP by 160 per tick<br />
Mana:  400, Casting Time:  4.0, Duration:  7 ticks, Recast Time:  3<br />
<br />
This would add some dps to our slow and work with our mana regen.  Again would add another resist check for slow (cold).  <br />
<br />
I do not think either of the above spells is overpowering, although maybe need some tweaks to costs/slow pct/etc to make the idea work.<br />
<br />
Summary:<br />
1.  Shm should *always* be better slowers than any other class<br />
2.  Make a slow to surpass BST slow in all situations<br />
3.  Tigirs upgrade?<br />
4.  Different resists or combination spells<br />
<br />
<h2>Nukes and DoTs</h2><br />
<br />
I lump these together because these are our bread and butter DPS.  Our current problems are that our Velium Strike nuke only does 925.  Other classes may be getting nuke upgrades in GoD which will illustrate further just how poor our nuke is.  <br />
<br />
If clerics and enchanters get a nuke upgrade, we should get a cold-based nuke for *AT LEAST* what they *used* to nuke for, i.e. 1100.  I have proposed a creative slow/nuke combo above.  A straight-up 1100 nuke would be easy to add.<br />
<br />
As far as DoTs go, Bane was nice, but the recast time sucks and it is resisted way too often.  The aggro on Bane is about where a DoT should be, however.  Ultor is only a soloing tool.  We do *NOT* need more DoTs to solo with.<br />
<br />
If a DoT is added, it should be FAST (perhaps 4 ticks or less even) and FURIOUS (at least 500/tick).  Basically a nuke in disguise.  Remember, we can only do this once per mob-that-dies-fast anyway.<br />
<br />
Here is my proposal for a straight up DoT:<br />
<br />
<b>Curse of the Kill-You-Fast</b><br />
1.  Decrease HP by 500 per tick<br />
2.  Increase Curse counter by 18<br />
Duration:  4 ticks, Mana:  500, Resist:  Magic, Recast Time:  6<br />
<br />
More mana, less efficient than bane, but more damage fast.  Although I propose this spell, we *did* get a magic-based DoT in LDoN, so maybe it should be something novel like cold, be evocation-based possibly?, or tack on other effects (as with Frigid Withering above).<br />
<br />
A long-lasting DoT (anything 1 min or more) does us no good at this point.  We got those nicely upgraded in PoP, and it is not a place where we need improvements.<br />
<br />
To sum up, we need burst dps, either a nuke of 1100+ or a 4-5 tick DoT doing 2kish damage.  If the devs find either of these overpowering, tack them on to a slow and make them cost more.<br />
<br />
Summary:<br />
1.  Better nuke<br />
2.  Faster high damage DoT<br />
<br />
<h2>Pets</h2><br />
<br />
Our pet is, above all else, fun.  I think of him like the cute dog in Nethack that follows you around.  He is basically a constant baseline DoT dps of about 40.  I do not think the pet needs to be the focus of attention for new expansions, nor does most of the shaman community.  All we really want with dogdog is innate dual wield and an easier way to haste him.  Adding 1-2 minor aa abilities devoted to pet is not a bad idea, but it should not be the focus of attention.  I think most shammies can agree on that.<br />
<br />
<h2>Melee</h2><br />
<br />
We used to be a battle priest.  We are no longer.  Clerics have taken this role.  I, personally, am fine with that.  I don't think it's feasible to make shaman melee in high end game anyway.  This is probably a point that will divide the shaman community... but I'd say most of the high-enders (65 w/aa) do not expect to kill a mob by smashing its face in.  The one possibility here is to fix Rabid Bear to be a real source of burst DPS, but, again, this is so minor compared to the other problems with the class.  <br />
<br />
One way to fix rabid bear is to have the form itself provide a benefit.  My personal favorite would be that being a rabid bear makes your poison and disease DoTs and nukes do more damage, because you are, after all, RABID!!  This would be similar to the wizard Iceflame of E'ci spell effect.  I don't consider this overpowering for high-enders at all, since we all have damage/dot foci anyway which wouldn't stack... but for those that didn't have these foci, it might be a very nice damage improvement.  I would suggest 25% improved damage to poison/disease dots/nukes while rabid bear is in effect.  I'd also up the tainted bite to be at least a 75dd.<br />
<br />
<h2>Buffs</h2><br />
<br />
With high-enders all stat-capped, our buffs have taken on less and less meaning.  Focus and FA are all we have left.  Group FA has been proposed.  I think this is a great idea.  In addition, I would like to see a group 60% haste for shaman, just because only the lazy of us bother with Talisman of Alacrity... so right now we labor to cast Swift Like the Wind on everyone.<br />
<br />
I don't think there is much more that can be done with buffs, other than giving us the endurance regen (which it looks like has been done).  <br />
<br />
Group FA has got to be the most requested buff (that I see).  Even if it is an AA, shammies everywhere would rejoice at its existence.<br />
<br />
Summary:<br />
1.  60% group haste<br />
2.  Group FA<br />
3.  Endurance regen<br />
<br />
<h2>Mana Regen</h2><br />
<br />
Along with slow, this is one of the core abilities of our class.  About all I can say about mana regen is, either seriously upgrade it or just leave it alone.  A half-assed upgrade would be the worst possible change.  If you're going to add a canni, I feel it should give the extra benefit of 10ish mana/tick when used once per minute.  In other words, an improvement of 60mana.<br />
<br />
My proposed canni spell would look like:<br />
<br />
<b>Cannibalize VI</b><br />
1.  Decrease HP by 250<br />
2.  Increase Mana by 140<br />
Casting Time:  3.5, Recast Time:  3.5<br />
<br />
I lengthen the casting time and recast time a bit, keep the hp-to-mana ratio pretty much the same, but make a genuine improvement to the hp gained.  If this were an aa, I would be wary of canni4/canni6 toggle being overpowered, so I would give a reuse time of 10 seconds or so in that case.<br />
<br />
<h2>Healing</h2><br />
<br />
Healing is, in my opinion, the most difficult aspect of the shaman class to nail down.  With the inception of EQ, we were definitely healers.  Now, we really aren't.  We are identified more as "slowers", an altogether different creature.  However, with the decreasing importance of slow in many situations (unslowable raid mobs, xp mobs that mitigate), it is important for a shaman to be able to keep up.  I'm not proposing that we ever be able to heal as well as a druid, but we shouldn't be ridiculously far behind them.<br />
<br />
Kragg's mending is just a bad spell.  No one uses it.  I would not propose any upgrade to it, as I don't see shamans as CH'ers, and most shamans on this board probably don't see themselves as CH'ers either.<br />
<br />
Tnargs is a pretty paltry fast heal.  Quiescence is nice, but other than healing our own canni, simply can't keep up with mitigated mobs.  It also doesn't help on raids when you need to heal someone outside your group.<br />
<br />
So, we need either a new fast heal or a new heal over time.  Group quiescence has been suggested, and I will take a stab at what that would look like:<br />
<br />
<b>Sphere of Quiescence</b><br />
1.  Increase HP v2 by 250 per tick<br />
<br />
Mana:  1000,  Casting Time: 7.0, Recast: 2.25, Target Type:  Group <br />
<br />
The idea is not to step on ethereal elixir (300/tick). or HoT the group in a more mana-efficient way than a cleric.  Hence 250, and 1000 mana cost.  Even adding something similar as an aa would make shammies happy.<br />
<br />
A new single target quiescence should look like this, I think:<br />
<br />
<b>Super Quiesce</b><br />
1.  Increase HP v2 by 400 per tick<br />
Duration:  4 ticks, Mana:  275, All else same as Q<br />
<br />
Summary:<br />
1.  Better fast heal<br />
2.  Better HoT<br />
3.  Group quiesce<br />
<br />
My final caveat with respect to both heals and nukes to the developers:   if you upgrade the healing and nuking capabilities of other classes without doing the same for shamans, we will fall very far behind.<br />
<br />
<h2>Debuffs</h2><br />
<br />
AE Malos has been suggested as a way to more quickly slow hordes of mobs.  Perhaps this is too powerful, but I mention it anyway.  An upgrade to cripple is also a frequent request.  Neither of these is high on my list, but different shammies have different priorities.<br />
<br />
I do believe debuffs could be made more creative, i.e. debuff+dot, debuff+nuke, etc.  similar to the ideas I tossed out there for the slow+nuke/slow+dot above.<br />
<br />
Summary:<br />
1.  Upgrade to cripple<br />
2.  AE Malos<br />
<br />
Well, that's about it.  I'm sure there will be lots of other ideas floating around in the next few weeks.  I've tried to mention everything I've ever seen anyone post on this board, even ideas that I am not personally a big fan of.<br />
<br />
Good luck, fellow shammies =)<br />
<br />
regards,<br />
Chifari of Magister, Erollisi Marr</p>
	
	
	
	
	
