<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Andal</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Initiate<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Oct 2002<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Just some observations on the elements of style in the proposal.  <br />
<br />
To be effective, presentation is as important as content.  I feel this initial draft lacks necessary elements of both style and content.<br />
<br />
The proposal needs to be directed to an individual.  It is too easy for everyone in a group to passively ignore something generally addressed. A person named must ignore with volition.<br />
<br />
If everyone simply mass complains using the exact same text, it will become nothing more than spam.  Really, really bad idea.  Much better to have one representative, and many signatories, with only one document sent.<br />
<br />
Anything bearing an accusatory tone needs to be removed.  For example: "through a medium of concentrated neglect".  The overall tone should not seem like a complaint, but rather a reasonable discussion of objective shortcomings.<br />
<br />
We do not know the motives of the balancing team as regards Shaman, to impute bad motives will not help our cause.  It would be unhelpful for us to proceed on the assumption that the developers have chosen to ignore or neglect, when in fact they may have ample and (to them) reasonable grounds for every decision they have made.<br />
<br />
Empty statements of objective opinion need to be removed, for example: "There is no reason that hybrids should be nuking on the same level us a pure caster class."<br />
<br />
Perhaps there is a reason, perhaps that reason is the subject of great and lengthy deliberation by very important and influential members of the balancing team, whose professional reputation and standing are entwined within.<br />
<br />
How can it aid us, then, to make such statements which could very well insult or at the least irritate those responsible for such things?  There are better ways to word things.<br />
<br />
Broad and subjective declarations need to be made specific.  There needs to be objective data serving to fortify each and every complaint.<br />
<br />
"Shaman healing is way behind other priests even when slow is factored in. Healing needs to be re-evaluated in comparison to other healing classes, including paladins. This review should include cast time, mana cost and amount healed."<br />
<br />
Have we any data to support this?  Does the data take into consideration all mitigating factors that might be relevant in issues of balance?<br />
<br />
Wouldn't it serve us better if it was *we* who did this evaluation using objective, repeatable methodolgy so we don't end up looking silly when somebody else shows us incontrovertable data proving we are wrong?<br />
<br />
Is it reasonable to lump all other priest classes together when making this comparison, or is it more relevant to make the comparison weighing the strengths and weaknesses of each priest class individually?<br />
<br />
I could play devil's advocate, and handily argue that none of the complaints in this proposal are accurate.  I can think of dozens of reasonable and plausible objections to every single point.<br />
<br />
To win at a game like this, you have to show more sand than just all getting together on a bunch of words.  You have to have solid, unarguable evidence.<br />
<br />
My opinion is the cart is going before the horse at this point, and much more work needs to be done.</p>
	
	
	
	
		<div class="smallfont"><i>Last edited by Andal on 01-15-2004 at <span class="time">11:48 PM</span>. </i></div>
	
	
