	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />That's quite a resist mod :P<hr size="1" /></blockquote>I really don't think a -55 resist mod on a slow is asking for all that much.  All it will do is make malos a debuff option instead of a requirement and allow us to lead with a slow instead of having to wait for malos to cast and then slowing.  This would give us the speed edge we've been asking for.  Well, something like that built in, or a new version of malos that's faster casting.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />The idea is not to step on ethereal elixir (300/tick). or HoT the group in a more mana-efficient way than a cleric. Hence 250, and 1000 mana cost.<hr size="1" /></blockquote>Why shouldn't ours be more mana efficient than a clerics?  Our single target HoTs are much more efficient than the cleric's version.  Don't forget that duration heals were our thing long before clerics picked them up.<br />
<br />
A quies upgrade is, in my mind, the most attractive way to boost our healing.  If you look at torpor (1200) vs. a druid's top fast-cast heal at level 60 (Nature's Touch, 978), we have the more powerful heal by over 20%, while still 25% less than a cleric's top fast heal (Ethereal Light, 1600).  In PoP, every priest had their general-duty blast heal effectively doubled in strength.  We got the shaft on this one since our best blast heal at the time was Superior Healing at 583hps.  Compare the upgrade we got for our workhorse heal, Quiescence, to Nature's Infusion (1750, almost 50% more than quies) and Supernal Light (2750, 150% more).  To stay in line with where we were before PoP, quies would need to do roughly 2100hps, or 525/tic.  This would also leave our blast heal at about the same as it was pre-PoP when Superior Healing and Chloroblast was all we had to work with, each being vastly inferior to the equivalent spells given to clerics and druids.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
